  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't something I've ever encountered directly as a mechanic, but I've seen it play out in the shop when younger mechanics talk about how their friends from school who wanted to be engineers or scientists sometimes get discouraged. I remember when my own kids were starting school, one of them was really into building robots and coding, but his teacher said, 'You're not the right type for this,' which made him doubt himself. Stereotype threat is when people feel anxious about confirming a negative stereotype about their group, like thinking they're not smart enough in math or science. It's not just about being a girl or a minority—it can affect anyone who's told they don't belong. For me, as a mechanic with lower secondary education, I've seen how important it is to support kids early on. If you tell a kid they can't do something, even if they're capable, it can hold them back. We should address it by creating environments where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. In Bari, where I live, there's a lot of community support for kids in workshops and after-school programs. These places teach kids that mistakes are part of learning, not a sign of failure. I think schools should do more to show kids that everyone can succeed in STEM, not just the ones who fit a certain mold. It's about changing the message we send, not just the curriculum. If we want to fix this, we need to start conversations with kids and their teachers before they start doubting themselves.",
